{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477482"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:02:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:02:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14559"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14559"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.11,0.19,0.15,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7252"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56905"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7252"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14559"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42359"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"6344"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17627"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44214"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56905"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her parents due to concerns about frequent urinary accidents. She has no history of previous urinary tract infections. Her parents report that she has always had difficulty controlling her bladder, but it has worsened recently. She was born at term with no complications during pregnancy or delivery. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals increased deep tendon reflexes in both lower limbs with bilateral ankle clonus and upgoing plantar responses. Muscle strength and tone in all limbs are normal. Sensory examination shows no loss of sensation. There are no musculoskeletal abnormalities or visible spinal lesions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Spina bifida occulta","Friedreich ataxia","Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease","Cerebral palsy","Idiopathic neurogenic bladder"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis for this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Espina bifida occulta\u003C/strong\u003E. The combination of upper motor neuron (UMN) signs in the legs (increased reflexes, ankle clonus, and upgoing plantar responses) along with urinary incontinence is highly suggestive of this condition. Spina bifida occulta is a mild form of spina bifida where the spinal cord and nerves are often affected, but there may be no visible abnormalities of the back.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral palsy\u003C/strong\u003E can present with UMN signs, but typically also involves muscle weakness or abnormal tone, which are absent in this patient. The normal musculoskeletal examination and isolated bladder symptoms make cerebral palsy less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECharcot-Marie-Tooth disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a peripheral neuropathy that typically presents with distal muscle weakness and sensory loss. The presence of UMN signs and the absence of sensory deficits in this patient make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFriedreich ataxia\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by progressive ataxia, absent lower limb reflexes, and sensory loss. The increased reflexes in this patient are inconsistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic neurogenic bladder\u003C/strong\u003E is a diagnosis of exclusion. While it can cause urinary symptoms similar to those described, it would not explain the UMN signs in the legs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to this diagnosis is recognising the combination of UMN signs in the legs and urinary incontinence without other significant neurological deficits. This presentation is characteristic of spina bifida occulta. Further investigations, such as MRI of the spine, would be necessary to confirm the diagnosis and determine the extent of the spinal cord involvement. Early diagnosis and management are crucial to prevent complications such as renal damage and to improve long-term outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Spina bifida occulta can present with upper motor neuron signs in the legs and urinary incontinence.","The presence of normal sensation and absence of musculoskeletal weakness helps differentiate spina bifida occulta from other neurological conditions.","Early diagnosis and management of spina bifida occulta are crucial to prevent complications and improve outcomes."],"references":["National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke (NINDS). Spina Bifida Information Page. National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke [Internet]. 2020 [cited 2024 Oct 20]. Available from: https://www.ninds.nih.gov/health-information/disorders/spina-bifida.","Spina Bifida Association. Occulta [Internet]. Spina Bifida Association. [cited 2024 Oct 20]. Available from: https://www.spinabifidaassociation.org/resource/occulta/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42359"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14559"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42359"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-22T14:23:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-22T14:25:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7252"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56905"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","sy